<dl id="n40039e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n40" href="#n40039e">N40 (VI.B.28B)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n40all.htm#n40039e"> 39(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> to devil</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">In English legal phraseology &ldquo;devil&rdquo; and &ldquo;devilling&rdquo; are used of barristers who act as substitutes for others. Any remuneration which the legal &ldquo;devil&rdquo; may receive is purely a matter of private arrangement between them. In the chancery division such remuneration is generally in the proportion of one half of the fee which the client pays; &ldquo;in the king&apos;s bench division remuneration for &lsquo;devilling&rsquo; of briefs or assisting in drafting and opinions is not common&rdquo; <small> &ldquo;DEVIL&rdquo; <a name="EBDV" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#EBDV"><cite title="source">Encyclopaedia Britannica</cite></a>, 11th edit. (1911) VIII 121</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
